value.value: The balance of oxidized and reduced molecules in the cell. Respiration and various environmental factors cause formation of reactive oxygen species which can oxidize and damage cellular components.
The ability to utilize the specified compound as a source of sulfur.

A form of cell death that is distinct from apoptosis. Cells undergoing necrotic cell death undergo overall destruction. They can be distinguished from apoptotic cells because they lose membrane integrity, which only happens late in apoptosis (positive propidium iodide staining), and do not externalize phosphatidylserine (measured by annexin V staining) as do apoptotic cells.
Formation of a septum between dividing cells.
The excretion from the cell of a specified chemical compound.
The outward appearance or shape of the mating projection.
Abundance of a specified RNA or class of RNAs.
Measures of the rate of recombination or total recombination observed during the mitotic cell cycle.
The size, shape, or appearance of subcellular organelles or structures.
The mutation results in a gene product that interferes with the function of the normal, wild-type gene product.

Classical genetics experiments carried out in a diploid background, where alleles of the gene being described are not identical.

A form of autophagy selective for peroxisomes that occurs in response to starvation, damage or as a homeostatic mechanism to regulate the levels of this organelle. Pexophagy can be further subdivided into micropexophagy, the engulfment of a cluster of peroxisomes at the vacuole surface and macropexophagy, the sequestration of individual peroxisomes by a double-membrane vesicle, followed by fusion with the vacuole.

A form of autophagy selective for mitochondria that occurs in response to starvation, damage or during a shift in environmental conditions. The process can be further subdivided into micromitophagy, the engulfment of a cluster of mitochondria at the vacuole surface, and macromitophagy, the sequestration of individual mitochondria by a double-membrane vesicle, followed by fusion with the vacuole.
The level of resistance to one or more cycles of freezing and thawing.

The size, shape, or appearance of lipid particles or droplets, subcellular structures consisting of a hydrophobic core of neutral lipids (triacylglycerol and steryl esters), surrounded by a phospholipid monolayer with a small quantity of embedded proteins including enzymes involved in lipid biosynthesis. Lipid particles function as a storage compartment for lipid components.
The size, shape or appearance of the Golgi apparatus or its parts.

Progression of cells through the mitotic cell cycle.

label.value: cell cycle progression in G2 phase

value.value: Progression of cells through the G2 phase or second gap phase of the mitotic cell cycle, the interval between the completion of DNA synthesis and the beginning of mitosis.

label.value: cell cycle progression in G1 phase

value.value: Progression of cells through the G1 or first gap phase of the mitotic cell cycle, the interval between the completion of mitosis and the beginning of DNA synthesis.

Passage of cells through cell cycle control point or checkpoint located late in the G1 phase of the mitotic cell cycle just prior to S phase entry; passage through START results in commits cells to progression through the entire cell cycle.

label.value: cell cycle progression through the G2/M phase transition

value.value: Progression of cells from G2 phase to M phase of the mitotic cell cycle.

label.value: cell cycle progression in M phase

value.value: Progression of cells through the M phase of the mitotic cell cycle, the phase in which mitosis occurs.

label.value: cell cycle passage through the metaphase-anaphase transition

value.value: Progression of cells from metaphase to anaphase during M phase of the mitotic cell cycle.
